DECISION STANDARD: BLOCK | PASS | PASS_WITH_FOLLOWUPS.

THE BLOCK (Codex): spawnDaemon() opened the log file via fs.open() and passed fh.fd to spawn() but
never closed the FileHandle, leaking the parent's fd / triggering Node's GC "Closing file descriptor"
warning. (All three seats flagged this fd issue; Codex escalated it to blocking.)

THE FIX (diff below):
(1) spawnDaemon now keeps the FileHandle, passes fh.fd to the child's stdio, then `await fh.close()`
    AFTER spawn() returns — the child has already dup'd the fd at spawn time, so it keeps its own
    copy while the parent closes its handle (no leak, no GC warning). Falls back to "ignore" if the
    log can't be opened.
(2) Hardening folded in from the other seats' follow-ups: (a) an unparseable line from the daemon now
    fails all pending requests + destroys the socket (instead of being ignored, which could hang a
    request forever under the default no-timeout); (b) request() wraps socket.write/encodeMessage in
    try/catch and clears the timer + pending entry + rejects on throw; (c) boolean CLI flags
    (--headless etc.) no longer consume the next token (so `bp --headless url` keeps url separate).

RE-VERIFICATION (objective, all PASS): the full separate-process acceptance script still passes
(auto-spawn, cross-process session reuse, pid stable, --json, console buffer survives across
processes, unknown-tool exit 2); no fd/GC warning observed on stderr.

JUDGE ONLY THE FIX: Is the fd leak fully closed and is closing the parent handle after spawn safe
(child keeps its dup)? Are the three hardening changes correct with no new regression (e.g. does
failAll-on-malformed-line over-react; does the try/catch double-settle the promise)?

